<br>
shadow<br>
<br>
 orc assasin x 4 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(319)">Orc Ambusher</a> x 4 <br>
 orc warband x 2 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(871)">Orc Scouting Band</a> x 4 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(156)">Orc Soldier</a> x 4 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(153)">Orc Hunters</a> x 1 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(133)">Band of the Eye</a> x 2 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(140)">Hate</a> x 2 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(163)">Thin and Stretched</a> x 1 (or another   <a href="javascript:card_browser(140)">Hate</a>, your choice) <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(321)">Under the Watching Eye</a> x4 <br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(150)">Orc Bowmen</a> x 4     </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> The combination of a hobbit only fellowship and direct damage from Sauron Orcs makes for a surprisingly effective deck. The deck focuses around Hobbit allies and the all hobbit fellowship with nasty conditions such as Under the Watching Eye and Orc Bowmen to slow the opponent down with constant damage. <br>
<br>
Site selection matters quite a bit with this deck as you will start with Green Hill Country, which reduces the cost of each hobbit by -1, as your site one, but you want to move second. You will then use the hobbit farmer to change to your site one when he comes up, and he inherits the text of your site one, which means all your allies play for free from then on! For site 2 you will use Buckleberry Ferry to avoid all skirmishes and save stealth cards for site 4 and 5 for another possible double move. Frodos Bedroom allows you to draw a card when you play a hobbit and with 11 in the deck you should be able to play at least one here. If you have sufficient stealth cards in your hand, and a bounder or two out, you may try to double move thru 4 and 5, but if in doubt then take it one site at a time. Use sting to see what they have in their hand in the regroup phase if you are considering double moving, and consider what shadow they are playing and where they will stop roaming. On the shadow side playing trackers first to lower roaming costs, followed by other minions that can exert to wound even if they cant win the skirmish allows you to pile on damage. Hate is used on archers that can exert to wound you, and particularly on exhausted companions. <br>
<br>
Your allies are really where the deck shines on the fellowship side. The Gaffer, Rosie, and Farmer Maggot can all exert to heal. Hobbit party guests exert to heal hobbits, and then heal themselves at the start of each turn. And the Hobbit farmer will reduce the cost of all hobbits by one by spotting your site one, making them all play for free. Bounders will keep the fellowship from being overwhelmed, and Frodo can heal one of them every turn. You NEED Thrór&#39;s Map by site 7 or your allies may be going bye bye at the Anduin Confluence! If you dont have the map out by then you may even let the opponent go ahead to avoid this, so your site 8 is played, or risk it and hope you can survive 3 sites without allies or that they dont play that site. <br>
<br>
The combination of Hate, Under the Watching Eye, and Orc Bowmen makes movement very painful for the opponent, and exert to wound minions will cause at least one dmg to opponents. Directed archery is risky for opponents as they may be Hated to death, and should be exerting alot anyway. <br>
